# Synload Cluster — Read-Only

The synload cluster is the production Kubernetes cluster where the prod
kaiad-agent (`kagent-5a78ae77…`) and the monitored services run. Its
kubeconfig is at `~/.kube/config_synload`.

## Binding rules

- **NEVER mutate the synload cluster.** Only read.
- Permitted `kubectl` verbs against synload: `get`, `describe`, `logs`,
  `top`, `version`, `api-resources`, `explain`, `config view`,
  `cluster-info`, `events`, and `--dry-run=client` previews.
- **Forbidden** against synload: `apply`, `create`, `delete`, `patch`,
  `edit`, `replace`, `scale`, `rollout restart/undo`, `annotate`,
  `label`, `cordon`, `drain`, `set`, `exec`, `cp`, `port-forward`,
  `attach`, `run`, or anything that writes to the cluster — directly or
  via the agent's `run_step`/command channel.
- Always target synload explicitly with
  `KUBECONFIG=~/.kube/config_synload` (or `--kubeconfig`). Never make it
  the default context. The default `~/.kube/config` (`kaiad-test`) is a
  separate, unrelated dev cluster.
- Any change to synload (e.g. rolling the agent pod, applying a CR) must
  be performed by the user. Provide exact commands; do not run them.

## Narrow exception — Kaiad-generated manifests only

The only permitted writes to synload are applying **Kaiad's own
generated manifests**, never hand-crafted cluster surgery:

1. KaiadAgent image/version bump: `kubectl -n kaiad-system patch
   kaiadagent <name> --type=merge -p
   '{"spec":{"image":"panel.kaiad.dev/kaiad-agent:<ver>"}}'` (+ a
   `rollout restart` of the agent Deployment if asked).
2. Applying the panel-served operator bundle
   (`panel.kaiad.dev/api/v1/operator/install.yaml`) and the
   panel-generated `KaiadAgent` CR from the #agents page.
3. The one-time `kubectl label namespace <ns> kaiad.dev/managed=true`
   the panel quickstart emits, so the operator-generated RBAC binds.

Everything else stays strictly read-only. No ad-hoc Role/RoleBinding/
Deployment/Service hand-editing, no changes to any non-kaiad workload.
Prefer fixing the generated manifests in the repo over patching the
cluster directly.
